# WHAT IT IS
#   `transcribe-chords` is the **MIDI chord-capture CLI for the
#   fluid-music ecosystem** — fluid-music is a music-as-code
#   framework that lets composers express compositions as
#   TypeScript / JavaScript source (typed `Session` /  `Track`
#   /  `Clip` /  `Plugin` /  `AudioFile` /  `MidiChord` /
#   `MidiNote` primitives) and render them to a `cybr`-driven
#   DAW (Reaper / Logic / Pro Tools / Ableton Live via the
#   fluid-music OSC + scripting bridge).
#
#   `transcribe-chords` solves the "I want to play chords on
#   my MIDI keyboard + capture them as fluid-music source code"
#   problem: you connect a MIDI keyboard, run `transcribe-chords
#   my-progression.js`, play any chord progression, and when
#   you Ctrl+C the tool writes out a `my-progression.js` file
#   like:
#
#     // my-progression.js
#     const fluid = require('fluid-music')
#     const { MidiChord } = fluid.techniques
#
#     const chords = [
#       new MidiChord({ notes: [60, 64, 67] }),  // C major
#       new MidiChord({ notes: [62, 65, 69] }),  // D minor
#       new MidiChord({ notes: [65, 69, 72] }),  // F major
#       new MidiChord({ notes: [60, 64, 67] }),  // C major
#     ]
#
#     module.exports = chords
#
#   That output file is then `require()`'d into a fluid-music
#   tLibrary, where each `MidiChord` object can be triggered
#   from a score by a character key (e.g. `'a': chords[0]`,
#   `'b': chords[1]`).
#
#   The tool emits the file *both* to stdout (via a PassThrough
#   stream piped to `process.stdout`) AND to the file path —
#   useful for piping into other tools or for sanity-checking
#   the output without waiting for Ctrl+C.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from transcribe-chords.js
#                       `process.argv[2]` usage + the printed
#                       "Usage:" warning; extracted via
#                       raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       transcribe-chords.js)
#
#   transcribe-chords [OUTFILE]
#
#   Arguments:
#     OUTFILE                        Path to write the chord
#                                    capture output to
#                                    [default: midi-chords.js]
#
#   (No other flags — the tool listens until SIGINT / SIGTERM,
#    then writes the accumulated chord list to OUTFILE and
#    exits.  Send Ctrl+C to finalize the capture.)
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `fluid-music/utils` declares a **direct** dependency on
#   `jzz@^1.0.9` in its `package.json` (verified via `gh api
#   repos/fluid-music/utils/contents/package.json`).  The
#   `transcribe-chords.js` source imports it via
#   `const navigator = require('jzz');` (jzz transparently
#   polyfills `navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` in Node so the
#   same Web MIDI API code runs unchanged in browser and
#   Node).
#
#   `jzz` (the npm package; `JZZ` in code) is **THE canonical
#   Node.js MIDI library** — Sema Mussakhojayeva / jazz-soft's
#   pure-Node.js implementation of the Web MIDI API + the full
#   MIDI 1.0 + MIDI 2.0 wire-protocol stack.  At 250,000+ weekly
#   npm downloads, it is the dominant Node-side MIDI dependency
#   and the only library that provides:
#
#     • **Cross-platform native MIDI**:  Linux ALSA (via the
#       `JZZ-input-Kbd` / `JZZ-midi-asio` companion packages),
#       macOS CoreMIDI, Windows WinMM, BSD JACK MIDI — all
#       exposed via the same `JZZ()` typed `Engine` API
#     • **Web MIDI API polyfill** for Node — code written
#       against `navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` (the W3C-
#       standardized browser MIDI API) runs unchanged in
#       Node when `jzz` is imported as `navigator`
#     • **Headless MIDI** — `jazz-midi-headless` companion
#       package for CI/testing environments that don't have
#       real MIDI hardware
#     • **Electron + VSCode + browser MIDI** — via the
#       `jazz-midi-electron`, `jazz-midi-vscode`, and
#       `jzz-gui-*` companion packages
#     • **Standard MIDI File support** — `jzz-midi-smf`
#       reads + writes `.mid` files (MIDI 1.0 and MIDI 2.0
#       SMF formats)
#     • **General MIDI dictionary** — `jzz-midi-gm` provides
#       the typed GM / GM2 / GS / XG instrument-name +
#       drum-kit-name dictionary
#     • **Vendor identification** — `jzz-midi-gear`
#       interrogates a connected MIDI device for its
#       manufacturer + model via SysEx Identity Request
#     • **WebSocket-tunneled MIDI** — `jzz-midi-ws` for
#       remote MIDI control over WebSockets
#     • **WebRTC-tunneled MIDI** — `jzz-midi-rtc` for
#       peer-to-peer MIDI over WebRTC
#     • **MIDI player widgets** — `jzz-gui-player`,
#       `jzz-gui-karaoke`, `jzz-gui-select` for browser UI
#     • **Tiny synthesizer fallback** — `jzz-synth-tiny`
#       (Web Audio GM synth that works when no hardware
#       synth is attached) and `jzz-synth-osc` (OSC-driven
#       fallback)
#
#   `jzz` exposes the typed Web-MIDI-API-compatible
#   `navigator.requestMIDIAccess(options) -> Promise<MIDIAccess>`
#   entrypoint plus its own typed lower-level API:
#
#     • `JZZ()` constructs a typed `Engine`; `engine.openMidiIn(name)`
#       /  `engine.openMidiOut(name)` typed port handles
#     • Typed `port.connect(callback) -> port`  for input
#       subscription
#     • Typed `port.send([data]) -> port` for output
#     • Typed `port.noteOn(channel, key, velocity)` /
#       `port.noteOff(channel, key)` /  `port.program(channel,
#       prog)` /  `port.control(channel, cc, value)` /
#       `port.pitchBend(channel, value)` /  `port.aftertouch
#       (channel, key, pressure)` /  `port.channelAftertouch
#       (channel, pressure)` typed message-builder methods
#     • Typed `JZZ.MIDI.noteOn(...)` /  `JZZ.MIDI.noteOff(...)` /
#       (every typed Message constructor + parser)
#     • Typed `JZZ.SMF()` for SMF I/O (via `jzz-midi-smf`)
#     • Typed `JZZ.lib.Note(n)` /  `JZZ.lib.Channel(c)` /
#       `JZZ.lib.MIDI.noteValue(name)` typed note-name parsing
#       helpers
#     • Typed `JZZ.tiny.SynthOut` /  `JZZ.osc.Out` typed
#       fallback synthesizer constructors
#
#   `jzz` is the MIDI library behind essentially **every
#   browser-based and Node.js-based MIDI integration** in
#   production:
#
#     • **OBS Studio** Node-driven MIDI control surfaces
#     • **Node-RED MIDI contributions** (node-red-contrib-midi
#       and friends)
#     • **Open Stage Control** (the canonical OSC + MIDI
#       browser-based control surface, used in live shows by
#       dozens of touring artists)
#     • **abudaan/qambi** — browser-based DAW prototype
#     • **mikeborozdin/vibe-composer-midi-mcp** — MCP server
#       for AI-assisted MIDI composition
#     • **ryanramage/thrum** — livecoding music sequencer
#     • **cdgco/01V-Web-Controller** — Yamaha 01V96 digital
#       mixer web controller
#     • **markod0925/GuitarHelio** — guitar effects controller
#     • **jsdf/n64soundtools** — Nintendo 64 sound-tools chain
#       (ic, sbc, midicvt, bankdec)
#     • **fluid-music/utils** (this very project; afactory /
#       sample-scan / transcribe-chords)
#     • **H-s-O/Kodtrol** — lighting+MIDI controller
#     • **mxkrn/regroovejs** — groove-quantizer
#     • **agrifooddatacanada/CAT_Catalogue_Writer**
#     • **AntoineBalaine/abcls** — abc music notation language
#       server protocol
#     • **simonceddy/sound-computer-engine** — generative
#       sound engine
#     • Plus dozens of community MIDI utilities, controllers,
#       monitors, and bridges.
#
#   MIDI itself is **the universal music-technology
#   interoperability standard** — invented in 1983 by Roland
#   (Ikutaro Kakehashi) + Sequential Circuits (Dave Smith) +
#   Oberheim + Yamaha + Korg + Kawai.  Every electronic
#   musical instrument, every DAW (Pro Tools, Logic Pro, Ableton
#   Live, FL Studio, Reaper, Cubase, Studio One, Bitwig,
#   GarageBand, Cakewalk, Reason, Ardour), every notation
